{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6efb38c5-73e0-40fa-8ea7-f70461c7daf5","content":"The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** crash dumps, not analyzing them. For **analyzing** a `.dmp` file, here are your best options:\n\n1. **`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n   dotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n   ```\n   Then use commands like `clrstack`, `pe` (print exception), `dumpheap`, etc.\n\n2. **Visual Studio** (Windows): Open the `.dmp` file directly — it provides a rich debugging UI with call stacks and exception info.\n\n3. **WinDbg** (Windows): Load the dump with the SOS extension for deep .NET diagnostics.\n\n4. **`lldb` + SOS** (Linux/macOS): For dumps collected on Linux.\n\nA quick starting workflow with `dotnet-dump analyze`:\n```\n> clrthreads          # list managed threads\n> setthread <id>      # pick the faulting thread\n> clrstack            # see managed call stack\n> pe                  # print last exception\n```\n\nWould you like help with any of these steps?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f23a167-e97a-4ba6-b886-9edb3ace240c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET app. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description says it's for **collecting** crash dumps, NOT for analyzing them. It explicitly states \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo I should NOT invoke the dump-collect skill. Instead, I'll provide guidance on how to analyze a .NET crash dump.","outputTokens":408,"requestId":"9423:634EC:184B975:1BACB1B:69E82103"},"id":"bd83e0ad-4f27-4697-8c63-487bc6927c61","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:14:55.445Z","parentId":"1c0b7a2c-2c19-464e-892e-d62058e88ca4"}
